{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/appendicitis/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"bd0bf4d1-012c-5b82-a8a7-992e85eea281","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field eaf0eb01-842f-43d2-b04a-785f8b181cc9 --><h2>What is it?</h2><!-- end field eaf0eb01-842f-43d2-b04a-785f8b181cc9 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item f08d7c77-8444-40b9-b39c-bae393dc1c8f --><!-- begin field c07118ff-e764-429a-b5b2-bfe90b584b50 --><ul><li>Appendicitis describes an acute inflammation of the appendix [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Gorter, 2016</a>].<ul><li>The appendix is a small, narrow tube (about 6–10 cm long) that is connected to the caecum (the proximal part of the large intestine, just before the colon).</li><li>Its precise function is not fully understood. It has a high concentration of gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT), and may act as a reservoir for normal gut flora, allowing the large bowel microbiome to recover after enteric infections [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Rentea, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/appendicitis/references/\">Stringer, 2017</a>].</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field c07118ff-e764-429a-b5b2-bfe90b584b50 --><!-- end item f08d7c77-8444-40b9-b39c-bae393dc1c8f -->","topic":{"id":"34a7018e-bdb2-5fb9-8f39-14b87cb77872","topicId":"38888cc0-af2f-4224-93a9-2ffe35d3793c","topicName":"Appendicitis","slug":"appendicitis","lastRevised":"Last revised in July 2020","chapters":[{"id":"c3867ccc-2088-5ea2-a8b8-c8a8fa3b1495","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"cadf0862-729f-56ee-b5c8-c92c5a72cbb5","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"i